    "plainContent": "Most UI libraries help you ship the first screen quickly, then make the tenth screen surprisingly expensive. The moment a product grows, every \"simple override\" starts turning into negotiation with somebody else's abstraction. That is the main reason feels different. It gives you components as source code, not as a sealed box. For a real product team, that difference is architectural, not cosmetic. The real value of a component system is not how fast it renders a demo. It is how calmly it survives the third redesign, the accessibility pass, and the feature request nobody predicted. <MetricCards items={ { label: 'Ownership', value: '100%', detail: 'Every component lives in your repo, so debugging and refactoring stay under your control.', }, { label: 'Typical payoff', value: '3 6 mo', detail: 'The real return shows up once the product starts accumulating variants and product edge cases.', }, { label: 'Biggest win', value: 'Clarity', detail: 'You keep the accessibility substrate while preserving authorship over API and visuals.', }, } / Why Source Owned UI Matters With , the component enters your repo as code you can read, rename, simplify, or delete. That changes the day to day development experience in a few important ways: you debug in your own codebase instead of inside library internals you style at the component boundary instead of fighting override layers you evolve the API gradually as product needs become clearer you keep ownership of naming, structure, and visual language In small demos, that may sound minor. In a growing app, it is the difference between \"we can adapt this today\" and \"we need a workaround again.\" A Typical Example Say we want a button component that supports variants, sizes, loading state, and icon placement without turning into a prop monster. This is not impressive because it is fancy. It is useful because the behavior is obvious, the styling stays local, and the API can evolve with the product. Radix Handles the Hard, Invisible Work The strongest part of the stack is not the classes. It is the accessibility foundation underneath. When builds on Radix primitives, you inherit a lot of painful details that teams often underestimate: keyboard navigation focus trapping escape key behavior ARIA semantics pointer and screen reader coordination Those are not \"nice extras.\" They are part of whether the component is production ready. A Quick Sanity Checklist x Button is reachable by keyboard x Dialog restores focus after close x Dropdown works with arrow keys x Labels and descriptions are announced correctly Final UX still needs product specific testing That last line matters. Accessible primitives reduce risk, but they do not replace thinking. <Callout type=\"tip\" title=\"What experienced teams do differently\" They stop treating accessibility as a QA phase and start treating it as a component API concern. That shift usually prevents more regressions than any late stage patching effort. </Callout Styling Feels Better When It Stays Near the Component One reason Tailwind pairs well with this setup is that styling remains close to structure and state. Instead of jumping between: 1. a component file 2. a theme override file 3. a CSS specificity battle 4. and sometimes library docs you often stay in one place and answer practical questions faster: where does this spacing come from? what changes on hover? which breakpoint affects this layout? why is the disabled state inconsistent? That local clarity is a huge advantage when onboarding teammates or reviewing UI bugs. <Compare leftTitle=\"Black box library mindset\" rightTitle=\"Source owned component mindset\" left={ 'Override first, understand later', 'Library API decides the shape of your product code', 'Fixes often depend on undocumented internals', 'Visual consistency can hide architectural rigidity', } right={ 'Read the implementation before you extend it', 'Product needs shape the final component API', 'Accessibility and behavior stay visible in the repo', 'Design system decisions become easier to teach and review', } / Where Teams Usually Go Wrong is not magic. Teams still create complexity if they copy components blindly and never curate them. Here is the failure mode I see most often: | Decision | Short term benefit | Long term cost | | | | | | Keep every generated prop | Faster setup | Bloated component API | | Add variants for every request | Fewer one off components | Hard to reason styling matrix | | Never delete old patterns | Avoid refactor today | Inconsistent design system later | | Skip accessibility review | Faster delivery | Expensive regressions | The fix is simple, but not always easy: treat copied components like product code, not like sacred vendor code. A Better Team Workflow If we were setting up the DiCodeWeb UI layer from scratch, I would keep the workflow intentionally disciplined: Then I would do three passes: <Steps <Step number=\"01\" title=\"Simplify first\" Delete props and variants the product does not need yet. A shorter API is usually easier to maintain than a theoretically flexible one. </Step <Step number=\"02\" title=\"Normalize the visual language\" Align radius, spacing, typography, and color tokens with the rest of the product so every copied primitive starts sounding like the same design system. </Step <Step number=\"03\" title=\"Stress test under real usage\" Try loading states, long labels, destructive actions, mobile layout, and keyboard only flows before declaring the component done. </Step </Steps That process keeps the component library from becoming a graveyard of copied snippets. The Most Important Mental Shift Teams often ask, \"Should we use a component library or build our own?\" With , the more useful question becomes: Which parts should we accelerate with high quality primitives, and which parts should remain fully ours? That framing leads to healthier architecture. You borrow the difficult accessibility substrate, but you keep authorship over the product experience. <Callout type=\"warning\" title=\"Common scaling trap\" If every engineer adds a new variant for every new screen, the design system will feel fast for two weeks and chaotic for six months. Copying components is easy. Curating them is the real job. </Callout When I Would Not Recommend It This approach is not perfect for every team. I would be more cautious if: the team wants a fully managed design system with minimal internal ownership designers and engineers do not yet have a shared UI vocabulary the product needs extremely rigid consistency across many repos immediately the team is likely to duplicate components without curation In those cases, a more opinionated system may create less operational drift. <Callout type=\"success\" title=\"Where it shines\" This stack is especially strong for teams that care about shipping quickly without giving up code ownership, accessibility, or the ability to evolve the design system inside the product. </Callout Final Take The best argument for is not that it looks modern. It is that it gives you a starting point that stays editable under real product pressure. You get: accessible primitives source ownership flexible composition local styling clarity a path toward a design system that grows inside your repo For DiCodeWeb, that is exactly the tradeoff that makes sense. We want speed, but not rented abstractions. We want polish, but also authorship. And we want a UI system that still feels understandable six months after the first copy paste."
